makin' a biopic.

84
00:09:48,720 --> 00:09:51,154
Really? I didn't
read that story.

85
00:09:53,360 --> 00:09:56,477
Yes, I've got
Mr Edward Wood on the line.

86
00:09:56,560 --> 00:09:58,391
Could you please hold?

87
00:10:00,400 --> 00:10:03,517
Mr Weiss?
Ed Wood here.

88
00:10:03,600 --> 00:10:07,673
Listen, I heard about your
new project and I was curious
if you'd signed a director yet.

89
00:10:07,760 --> 00:10:09,591
Oh, you haven't!

90
00:10:09,680 --> 00:10:11,989
Well, if we could get together,
I could explain to you...

91
00:10:12,080 --> 00:10:15,834
why I'm more qualified to direct
this than anyone else in town.

92
00:10:17,080 --> 00:10:20,629
Well, I'd rather not
go into that over the phone.

93
00:10:20,720 --> 00:10:22,790
All right.
Great!

94
00:10:22,880 --> 00:10:25,553
I'll see you then.
Bye!

95
00:10:25,640 --> 00:10:27,676
Eddie, I don't understand.

96
00:10:27,760 --> 00:10:30,991
Why are you the most qualified director
for the Christine Jorgensen story?

97
00:10:31,080 --> 00:10:33,594
Oh, it's just hogwash, hon.
I had to get into the door somehow.

98
00:10:33,680 --> 00:10:35,511
[Chuckles]

99
00:10:43,880 --> 00:10:46,838
[Engine Knocking]

100
00:10:46,920 --> 00:10:49,718
[Sputtering]

101
00:10:53,920 --> 00:10:55,751
[Man]
No, I love you like a brother.

102
00:10:55,840 --> 00:10:59,071
No, no, no. No, no, no.
That's a fialsehood!

103
00:11:00,800 --> 00:11:02,677
Come in!

104
00:11:02,760 --> 00:11:07,959
Look, when I said you could
have the western territories,
I didn't mean all 1 1 states!

105
00:11:08,040 --> 00:11:11,669
I meant California, Oregon,
and what's that one on top?

106
00:11:11,760 --> 00:11:13,591
Washington, yeah, yeah!

107
00:11:13,680 --> 00:11:15,796
W... Oh, really?

108
00:11:15,880 --> 00:11:17,757
Well, screw you!

109
00:11:17,840 --> 00:11:20,513
Hi. Can I help you?

110
00:11:20,600 --> 00:11:23,512
Yes. I'm Ed Wood.
I'm here about directing the
Christine Jorgensen picture.

111
00:11:23,600 --> 00:11:26,160
[Chuckling]
Well, a couple of things have changed.

112
00:11:26,240 --> 00:11:28,595
It ain't gonna be the
Christine Jorgensen story no more.

113
00:11:28,680 --> 00:11:31,752
Goddam Variety had to print
the story before I got the rights.

114
00:11:31,840 --> 00:11:34,274
- Now that bitch is asking for the sky.
- Ah, you're not gonna make the movie.

115
00:11:34,360 --> 00:11:39,388
No, of course I'm gonna make
the picture. I already presold
Alabama and Oklahoma.

116
00:11:39,480 --> 00:11:42,552
Those repressed Okies, they go for
that twisted, perverted stuff.

117
00:11:42,640 --> 00:11:45,438
We'll just do it without the she-male.
We'll fictionalize it.

118
00:11:45,520 --> 00:11:49,638
- Is there a script?
- Fuck no. But, there's a poster.

119
00:11:52,120 --> 00:11:54,953
It opens in nine weeks
in Tulsa.

120
00:11:55,040 --> 00:11:57,315
Well, Mr Weiss, look no further.
I'm your man.

121
00:11:57,400 --> 00:12:01,154
I work fast and I'm a deal.
I write and direct. And I'm good.

122
00:12:01,240 --> 00:12:04,869
I just did a play in Hollywood
and Victor Crowley himself
praised its realism.

123
00:12:04,960 --> 00:12:07,713
There's about 500 guys in this town
that can say the same thing.

124
00:12:07,800 --> 00:12:11,076
On the phone you said you had
some special qualifications?

125
00:12:16,280 --> 00:12:18,111
Mr Weiss...

126
00:12:19,160 --> 00:12:21,390
I have never told anyone...

127
00:12:21,480 --> 00:12:23,550
what I'm about to tell you.

128
00:12:23,640 --> 00:12:25,949
But I really want
this job.

129
00:12:28,920 --> 00:12:31,229
I like to dress
in women's clothing.

130
00:12:32,280 --> 00:12:34,510
You're a fruit?

131
00:12:34,600 --> 00:12:38,752
No, not at all. I love women.
Wearing their clothes makes me
feel closer to them.

132
00:12:38,840 --> 00:12:42,515
- You're not a fruit.
- No, I'm all man.
I even fought in W.W. Two.

133
00:12:42,600 --> 00:12:45,592
Of course, I was wearing women's
undergarments under my uniform.

134
00:12:45,680 --> 00:12:48,148
Ya got to be kidding me.

135
00:12:48,240 --> 00:12:50,993
Confidentially, I even paratrooped
wearing a brassiere and panties.

136
00:12:51,080 --> 00:12:53,878
I tell ya, I wasn't scared
of being killed, but I was
terrified of getting wounded...

137
00:12:53,960 --> 00:12:56,599
and having the medics
discover my secret.

138
00:12:56,680 --> 00:13:00,355
- So you think this qualifies you
to make my movie?
- Yes!

139
00:13:00,440 --> 00:13:03,318
I know what it's like
to live with a secret...

140
00:13:03,400 --> 00:13:06,676
and worry about what people
are gonna think of ya.

141
00:13:06,760 --> 00:13:09,752
My girlfriend still doesn't know why
her sweaters are always stretched out.

142
00:13:11,240 --> 00:13:14,710
Ed, you seem like a nice kid.
Look around you.

143
00:13:14,800 --> 00:13:18,270
I don't hire directors with burning
desires to tell their stories.

144
00:13:18,360 --> 00:13:20,271
I make movies
like Chained Girls.

145
00:13:20,360 --> 00:13:23,955
I need someone with experience
who can shoot a film in four
days and make me a profit.

146
00:13:24,040 --> 00:13:26,508
I'm sorry.
That's all that matters.

147
00:13:29,840 --> 00:13:32,229
Can I get you
anything else, kid?

148
00:14:19,360 --> 00:14:22,670
Too constrictive!
I can't even fold my arms.

149
00:14:22,760 --> 00:14:24,955
Gee, Mr Lugosi,
I've never had any complaints.

150
00:14:25,040 --> 00:14:28,157
This is the most uncomfortable coffin
I've ever been in.

151
00:14:28,240 --> 00:14:31,789
Your selection is quite shoddy.
You're wasting my time!

152
00:14:33,680 --> 00:14:36,638
- Mr Lugosi?
- I told you I don't want any
of your goddam coffins!

153
00:14:36,720 --> 00:14:39,029
No, no!
I don't work here.

154
00:14:39,120 --> 00:14:42,078
- Then who are you? What do you want?
- I don't want anything.

155
00:14:42,160 --> 00:14:46,915
- I'm just a really big, big fan.
I've seen all your movies.
- [Scoffs]

156
00:14:49,840 --> 00:14:53,435
-Mr Lugosi, why are you buying a coffin?
-I'm planning on dying soon.

157
00:14:53,520 --> 00:14:57,115
- No!
- Yes! I'm embarking on another
bus and truck tour of Dracula.

158
00:14:57,200 --> 00:14:59,998
Twelve cities in ten days,
if that's conceivable.

159
00:15:00,080 --> 00:15:03,516
Do you know that I saw you perform
Dracula in Poughkeepsie in 1 938?

160
00:15:03,600 --> 00:15:07,832
- That was a terrible production.
Renfield was a drunk!
- I thought it was great.

161
00:15:07,920 --> 00:15:11,196
You know, you're much scarier
in real life than you are in the movie.

162
00:15:11,280 --> 00:15:13,111
Thank you.

163
00:15:13,200 --> 00:15:15,668
I even waited outside to get your
autograph, but you never came out.

164
00:15:15,760 --> 00:15:18,718
Well, I apologize. When I play Dracula,
I put myself into a trance.

165
00:15:18,800 --> 00:15:21,109
It takes me much time
to reemerge.

166
00:15:22,440 --> 00:15:25,716
Oh, there's my bus.
Shit, where is my transfer?

167
00:15:25,800 --> 00:15:28,598
- Say, don't you have a car?
- I refuse to drive in this country.

168
00:15:28,680 --> 00:15:30,511
Too many madmen.

169
00:15:31,400 --> 00:15:33,675
I've got a car.

170
00:15:33,760 --> 00:15:36,069
[Engine Knocking]

171
00:15:38,920 --> 00:15:42,037
Boy, Mr Lugosi, you must lead
such an exciting life.

172
00:15:42,120 --> 00:15:46,352
- When is your next picture coming out?
- I have no next picture.

173
00:15:46,440 --> 00:15:50,513
You gotta be jokin'.
A great star like you, you must
have dozens of'em lined up.

174
00:15:50,600 --> 00:15:52,909
Back in the old days, yes.

175
00:15:53,000 --> 00:15:55,833
But now, no one gives
two fucks for Bela.

176
00:15:55,920 --> 00:15:58,992
- But you're a big star.
- No more.

177
00:15:59,080 --> 00:16:01,071
I haven't worked
in four years.

178
00:16:02,600 --> 00:16:06,593
This business, this town,
it chews you up, then spits you out.

179
00:16:06,680 --> 00:16:10,958
I'm just an ex-bogeyman.
Make a right.

180
00:16:20,720 --> 00:16:24,030
[Radiator Hissing,
Engine Knocking, Wheezing]

181
00:16:24,120 --> 00:16:26,918
They don't want the classic
horror films any more.

182
00:16:28,040 --> 00:16:31,237
Today, it's all giant bugs.

183
00:16:31,320 --> 00:16:33,914
Giant spiders,
giant grasshoppers.

184
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:35,831
Who would believe
such nonsense?

185
00:16:35,920 --> 00:16:40,038
The old ones were much spookier;,
they had castles and full moons.

186
00:16:40,120 --> 00:16:41,951
They were mythic.

187
00:16:42,040 --> 00:16:44,349
- They had a poetry to them.
- Yes.

188
00:16:44,440 --> 00:16:47,238
And you know what else?
The women...

189
00:16:47,320 --> 00:16:51,233
The women prefer
the traditional monsters.

190
00:16:51,320 --> 00:16:53,151
The women. Huh.

191
00:16:53,240 --> 00:16:57,233
The pure horror, it both repels
and attracts them.

192
00:16:57,320 --> 00:16:59,959
Because in their
collective unconsciousness...

193
00:17:00,040 --> 00:17:02,270
they have the agony
of childbirth.

194
00:17:02,360 --> 00:17:05,955
The blood...
The blood is horror.

195
00:17:07,400 --> 00:17:09,231
You know,
I never thought of that.

196
00:17:11,240 --> 00:17:13,071
Take my word for it.

197
00:17:13,160 --> 00:17:15,720
If you want to make out
with a young lady...

198
00:17:15,800 --> 00:17:20,430
you take her to see Dracula.
[Chuckling]

199
00:17:24,040 --> 00:17:25,871
[Dogs Whining,
Barking]

200
00:17:25,960 --> 00:17:27,791
Eh, what a mess.

201
00:17:27,880 --> 00:17:30,678
My wife of 20 years
left me last month.

202
00:17:30,760 --> 00:17:33,069
- I'm not much of a housekeeper.
- [Dogs Barking]

203
00:17:33,160 --> 00:17:37,039
- All right, I'm coming.
I'll feed you, my darlings.
- I'd better get going.

204
00:17:37,120 --> 00:17:40,590
But perhaps we could get together
again some time, Mr Lugosi.

205
00:17:41,640 --> 00:17:43,471
Certainly.

206
00:17:43,560 --> 00:17:47,997
But now, the children of the night
are calling me. [Chuckling]

207
00:17:48,080 --> 00:17:50,799
Uh...
[Nervous Chuckle]

208
00:17:50,880 --> 00:17:52,711
- Good day.
- Good day.

209
00:17:56,080 --> 00:17:58,992
Sweetie, you won't believe it.
I've got incredible news.

210
00:17:59,080 --> 00:18:01,719
- You got the job!
- No, I didn't get the job.

211
00:18:01,800 --> 00:18:05,190
- But something better happened.
- Better than not getting the job.

212
00:18:05,280 --> 00:18:07,953
Yes!
I met a movie star.

213
00:18:08,040 --> 00:18:11,635
- Somebody really big.
- Who? Robert Taylor?

214
00:18:11,720 --> 00:18:14,712
No. A horror movie star.

215
00:18:14,800 --> 00:18:17,030
- Boris Karloff?
- Close.

216
00:18:17,120 --> 00:18:19,588
The other one.

217
00:18:19,680 --> 00:18:22,478
You met...
Basil Rathbone!

218
00:18:22,560 --> 00:18:25,677
Oh, to heck with you.
I met Bela Lugosi.

219
00:18:25,760 --> 00:18:29,992
- Why, I thought he was dead.
- No, he's very much alive.

220
00:18:30,080 --> 00:18:31,433
Well...

221
00:18:31,520 --> 00:18:33,511
sort of.

222
00:18:33,600 --> 00:18:37,718
He's old and frail, but he's still
Bela Lugosi and he's really nice.

223
00:18:37,800 --> 00:18:41,270
- I can't even remember the last
time I saw him in a picture.
- It's a shame.

224
00:18:41,360 --> 00:18:43,669
He's such a great actor
and no one uses him any more.

225
00:18:43,760 --> 00:18:46,479
-So, did you get his autograph?
-No, it wasn't like that at all.

226
00:18:46,560 --> 00:18:50,712
It was just the two of us and we were
talking. He treated me like a friend.

227
